column38: F. Henkel, Die römischen Fingerringe der Rheinlande und der benachbarten Gebiete (1913) pl. 55.1424, 1440; 56.1450. Significance of iron rings according to Pliny N. H. that in the early Roman Republic iron was the common material for a ring, "The hand and indeed the left gave gold the greatest aspect, but not for a Roman, because his ring was of iron, a symbol of warlike courage" (Pliny N. H. 33, 4). Further, Pliny observed, that still 100 years before Vespasian's reign senators, who wished to exhibit a speical simplicity and old Roman style, wore iron rings. And c. mid 1st cent. AD iron rings signified equestrians and   magistrates (Pliny N. H. 33,8).

column14: Iron finger-ring; narrow hoop with triangle-shaped widened shoulders and plate-like widened upper side; in latter a glass-paste copy of "Nicolo" is inlaid; opaque black with opaque blue overlaid on the scene side. The glass-paste is a high conical polished oval, the scene surface is flat. Description: a bearded man sits facing left on a rock, his upper body is naked, a cloak is laid around his lower body and knees; with both hands he holds a scroll; in front of him sits a bearded herm with a short staff. This representation is found particularly on republican and early imperial gems.

column15: Thanks to H. U. Nuber and  H.G. Simon for the reading of the inscription, that led to the following: the plate has four groups of incised inscriptions and one punched inscription. The punched inscription on the rim is clear and reads: 'T.GRATI FLAVI'. Because of heavy corrosion of the surface the incised inscriptions are only partly discernible: 1. on the lower rim: 'GRATI FLAVI'; it can no longer be ascertained, whether the name 'Gratus', as in the incised inscription, is preceded by the declaration 'T(urma)' . 2. Of the first inscription to the left of the central part of the plate only the letter 'L' is  evident, the rest in no longer explicable. 3. The beginning of the word in the middle group is destroyed,  the end' .... AVIS' is probably the genitive of a personal name. 4. The last incised inscription includes the same name, 'FLAVI', that has already appeared in the punched inscription and the first incised inscription. The punched inscription follows the customary scheme of the ownership declaration on military equipment: the declaration of the Turma with the cognomen of the decurion, Gratus, followed by the cognomen of the owner, Flavus. Independent of grave finds, this infers a cavalry troop at Oberstimm, an Ala or a cohors equitata. The graffito 'Imaginifer' (graffito C818 = cat.no. C375) gives additional corroboration. Both cognomina are widely distributed: The name Gratus is especially frequently found in the Narbonensis, Flavus in Spain; according to Kajanto more than half of all the individuals siezed with this name are from the Spanish provinces. From the lack of all further evidence  one would certainly not hold this alone as a key to the recruitment of the troop. Both names appear again in an incised inscription; possibly the indistinct incision was replaced by the more legible puncturing. The three higher placed incised inscriptions, Nos 2-4 permit more possible interpretations, except that the preservation allows one decision: in the illegible inscription no. 2 one can presume the name of a decurion, the name of another owner ending in '... avis' ; the name 'Flavi' (no. 4) would then be only a further repetition. Equally it would be possible, to see in '.. avis' the name of a decurion, in 'Flavus'  that of the owner. The inscription no. 2 could then include the name of another owner or all three inscriptions form the name of a unit and no. 2 includes the declaration of the troop unit.

One-sided greenish-grey glass melted crust, c. 10 qcm; investigated non-invasively by Dr. H.-G. Bachmann, Frankfurt a. M.  (X-ray fluorescent analysis elements mit atomic weight over 22):"The purpose of the analysis was to discern whether the piece originated from the lining or wall of a metallurgical hearth or oven. The vitrification of the cement-like sample could have been caused only through intensive heat action, which suggests the origin of the piece from an over or similar. The analysis (half-quantitative) showed, that the sample contains only the heavy element iron (order of magnitute l - 5%) and traces of rubidium, zircon, manganese und titanium. All these elements are typical components of rock, clay and loam, used for ovens and furnaces or other strong structures. Alloy metals are completely missing. Also the iron content is much too low for the sample to be associated iron extraction or processing. On the other hand althought the temperatures leading to the vitrification of the surface must have been too high, to explain an origin of the piece from a cooking oven or cooking place, it could be accepted, with reservation, that it was a part of the plaster-covered wall of a furnace canal or space of a heating location (bath?), a ceramic kiln  (pottery or tile) or a glass oven. The piece is too unspecific to allow further conclusions."
